1
00:00:00,571 --> 00:00:25,632
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa

2
00:00:26,137 --> 00:00:30,463
homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble, and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:31,984 --> 00:00:45,783
So I thought this evening I'd tackle this neoliberalism, save us all, and the role of Buddhism, of Buddha Dharma, in that particular ideology.

4
00:00:46,405 --> 00:00:51,451
So just to remind ourselves an ideology is just a, you know,

5
00:00:51,770 --> 00:00:55,415
a set of beliefs and principles that go on to a policy.

6
00:00:55,817 --> 00:01:04,551
But as an ideology, as an idealism as well, there's always some future goal, some sort of Shangri-La that it's always heading towards.

7
00:01:05,412 --> 00:01:17,271
And it always has, even in Marxist terms, that the seed of destruction,

8
00:01:17,638 --> 00:01:21,606
is always in capitalism.

9
00:01:22,028 --> 00:01:27,498
But that's true, as we've discovered from the last century, of any ideology, right?

10
00:01:27,558 --> 00:01:36,575
Communism, national socialism, even democracy, but democracy at least has this sort of self-correction every so often.

11
00:01:37,281 --> 00:01:44,852
And as we've discovered, it only really works when the society tends to be fairly peaceful with itself.

12
00:01:44,953 --> 00:01:51,462
As we see these days, there's a leaning towards the right again, towards authoritarianism.

13
00:01:53,445 --> 00:01:59,353
So the Buddha himself didn't fashion Buddhism.

14
00:01:59,655 --> 00:02:06,765
He simply taught a practical path to liberators and the understanding that underlines it.

15
00:02:06,914 --> 00:02:12,401
So it's really about ethics, you know, and he belonged to a period before writing.

16
00:02:13,103 --> 00:02:19,233
So therefore, there isn't this philosophy and, you know, systems theory and all that.

17
00:02:19,332 --> 00:02:20,975
It just didn't exist at that time.

18
00:02:22,076 --> 00:02:24,039
The thought was really very practical.

19
00:02:26,243 --> 00:02:34,355
Now, the fundamental attitude that actually drives neoliberalism is greed, acquisitiveness.

20
00:02:34,723 --> 00:02:41,513
I'm just quoting here from Oliver Stone's movie, which was in 1987 called Wall Street.

21
00:02:42,153 --> 00:02:43,134
Some of you might have seen it.

22
00:02:43,376 --> 00:02:48,102
Gordon Gekko is the sort of antihero played by Michael Douglas.

23
00:02:48,162 --> 00:02:54,790
And he gives this speech and he says, the point is, ladies and gentlemen, that greed, for lack of a better word, is good.

24
00:02:55,831 --> 00:02:56,652
Greed is right.

25
00:02:56,734 --> 00:02:57,495
Greed works.

26
00:02:57,754 --> 00:03:03,802
Greed clarifies, cuts through and captures the essence of the evolutionary spirit of

27
00:03:04,002 --> 00:03:12,293
Greed in all its forms, greed for life, greed for money, for love, knowledge, has marked the upward surge of mankind.

28
00:03:12,872 --> 00:03:13,995
My, doesn't sound.

29
00:03:15,856 --> 00:03:20,103
So what it does is it makes you a very special human being.

30
00:03:20,223 --> 00:03:21,584
You know, you're out for yourself.

31
00:03:23,026 --> 00:03:28,693
This sort of very selfish attitude that I should have what I want when I want it.

32
00:03:29,213 --> 00:03:33,840
If you remember Frank Sinatra's old song, you know, I did it my way.

33
00:03:35,557 --> 00:03:38,341
And of course, it's a corruption of what Darwin said.

34
00:03:39,521 --> 00:03:49,450
Darwin, I quote him here, it is not the strongest of the species that survive, not the most intelligent, but the ones most responsive to change.

35
00:03:49,890 --> 00:03:53,074
So this word fittest actually means adaptable.

36
00:03:54,375 --> 00:04:05,564
But ever since the beginning of the Industrial Revolution, we've had this idea that there'll come a time when we can produce enough stuff so that everybody has everything.

37
00:04:09,223 --> 00:04:13,090
So there's a couple of books here that I can mention towards the end.

38
00:04:13,129 --> 00:04:14,211
I might come back to that.

39
00:04:14,711 --> 00:04:21,742
But I just mentioned this book by Jill Westcott called The Psychological Roots of the Climate Crisis.

40
00:04:22,303 --> 00:04:27,432
And it sort of brings together many things.

41
00:04:27,591 --> 00:04:37,526
But one thing that she points out is that the wealthy nurtured the concept of neoliberalism through right-wing think tanks, and they captured the republicans

42
00:04:37,776 --> 00:04:39,158
and eventually the Tories.

43
00:04:39,639 --> 00:04:41,581
So that's dear old Margaret Thatcher for us.

44
00:04:43,903 --> 00:04:52,673
So now this acquisitiveness, this greed, it operates in a market, right?

45
00:04:52,754 --> 00:05:01,302
So we're all now entrepreneurs in this market and we all want everything all at once.

46
00:05:03,055 --> 00:05:08,461
And what it does, of course, is it creates this competition.

47
00:05:10,524 --> 00:05:18,396
But of course, it's a competition that is antagonistic because either you're my, at best, my rival, at worst, you're my direct enemy.

48
00:05:18,956 --> 00:05:22,802
So I'm always working against somebody.

49
00:05:26,139 --> 00:05:35,593
Now, you can't say that competition is bad, is all bad, because it does actually create efficiency and inventiveness.

50
00:05:35,673 --> 00:05:46,427
In fact, in the worst cases where you have this aggressive competition war in the Second World War, remember,

51
00:05:47,403 --> 00:05:52,189
Jet planes, jet engines, radar, and the computer were developed.

52
00:05:52,550 --> 00:05:55,935
So there's a tremendous irony there.

53
00:05:56,475 --> 00:06:04,326
But the thing is that what neoliberalism presumes is that society is at best when it services the market.

54
00:06:04,807 --> 00:06:06,050
We're all individuals.

55
00:06:06,149 --> 00:06:11,677
We're all working against each other in order to get the biggest piece of the pie we can.

56
00:06:11,737 --> 00:06:14,862
And the whole process is very antagonistic.

57
00:06:16,512 --> 00:06:25,002
But when you look at something like academia, where scientists from all over the world might be working on a particular project,

58
00:06:25,303 --> 00:06:28,387
They're very happy to share with each other their discoveries.

59
00:06:28,968 --> 00:06:32,512
Now, they're not motivated by power or money.

60
00:06:32,531 --> 00:06:34,033
I mean, they're given a salary.

61
00:06:35,254 --> 00:06:42,000
I mean, they might covet the Nobel Prize, but it's usually just sheer interest in the scientific investigation.

62
00:06:42,302 --> 00:06:48,507
So here we have a collaborative competitiveness, which is a very different atmosphere altogether.

63
00:06:50,329 --> 00:06:53,033
I think it's something the Buddha would have liked.

64
00:06:56,000 --> 00:07:04,507
Now, the downside of this, of course, is that if you're not a player in the market, then in a sense, you've only yourselves to blame.

65
00:07:05,197 --> 00:07:05,958
Right?

66
00:07:06,999 --> 00:07:20,358
And in blaming the victims, if you remember going back to Thatcher period, those from the rest of Europe won't remember this, but we had this fellow called Tebbit who told people to get onto their bikes, you know?

67
00:07:20,377 --> 00:07:21,959
Like, it's up to you.

68
00:07:22,019 --> 00:07:23,302
You've got to get the work.

69
00:07:23,341 --> 00:07:26,045
And if you don't get the work, well, that's your problem.

70
00:07:26,245 --> 00:07:26,927
You're to blame.

71
00:07:27,747 --> 00:07:35,017
So workers begin to lose their rights because basically you have to negotiate with your employer.

72
00:07:35,132 --> 00:07:44,283
And the competition between workers determines the cost, which will go down and down.

73
00:07:44,362 --> 00:07:46,565
So this is the gig economy, isn't it?

74
00:07:46,586 --> 00:07:49,028
This is what we mean by the race to the bottom.

75
00:07:49,528 --> 00:07:52,451
So I give a definition here of a race to the bottom.

76
00:07:52,872 --> 00:07:59,519
A competitive situation where a company, a state, or a nation attempts to undercut

77
00:07:59,500 --> 00:08:09,122
the competition's prices by sacrificing quality standards or worker safety or reducing labour costs.

78
00:08:09,776 --> 00:08:21,315
And you can see, for instance, when Uber started in London, I'm hoping that the situation is the same in the rest of the world, or I'm not sure.

79
00:08:22,677 --> 00:08:27,505
Basically, those who wanted to join Uber were in competition with each other.

80
00:08:28,007 --> 00:08:30,029
So you can imagine Uber.

81
00:08:30,567 --> 00:08:47,951
a parent who has children, holidays and all that sort of stuff, a young woman who has a mortgage, et cetera, and a young fella who's got no problems whatsoever, he's only about 21 or something,

82
00:08:47,932 --> 00:08:50,676
And they are bidding for your ride.

83
00:08:51,197 --> 00:09:05,998
Well, if the man with all the, if the parent with all the problems is charging you 30 and the woman charges you 25 and he charges you 20, then if the parent wants that ride, they've got to come all the way down to 20.

84
00:09:07,480 --> 00:09:08,360
And that's what happens.

85
00:09:08,421 --> 00:09:10,563
Everything starts moving downwards.

86
00:09:11,775 --> 00:09:18,761
The worst example, of course, is this recent sacking of 800 workers by the P&O ferry line.

87
00:09:19,682 --> 00:09:29,392
Interestingly enough, they were losing 100 million, but at the same time, they paid out 270 million to their dividend, to their shareholders.

88
00:09:30,332 --> 00:09:33,716
So you can see it's not very fair, is it?

89
00:09:38,500 --> 00:09:41,243
And we all know about this tremendous...

90
00:09:41,341 --> 00:09:44,369
Well, it comes out to be a lie, doesn't it?

91
00:09:44,389 --> 00:09:51,727
This this thing about trickle down, you know, eventually the wealth sort of trickles down and everybody's happy.

92
00:09:52,269 --> 00:09:58,184
But it doesn't trickle down to the unemployed, to the disabled or the old, the aged.

93
00:09:58,164 --> 00:10:02,230
And these players, of course, are not in the market.

94
00:10:02,812 --> 00:10:06,937
So now that would be a real drag, draining money from the market.

95
00:10:06,957 --> 00:10:14,788
So the only way to get around that is, of course, to privatize all the social services so that these companies get their 10%.

96
00:10:15,529 --> 00:10:24,503
I don't know what's happening in the rest of Europe, but now there are many GP surgeries that are being taken over by a company called Centene.

97
00:10:24,923 --> 00:10:27,868
And even the Daily Mail said it was the most

98
00:10:27,847 --> 00:10:31,812
avaricious of insurance companies.

99
00:10:31,831 --> 00:10:33,254
So it's all bad news, isn't it?

100
00:10:35,054 --> 00:10:40,860
But the big thing is, of course, is that this competition just undermines a sense of common wealth.

101
00:10:41,802 --> 00:10:46,246
It's no longer a caring society.

102
00:10:46,267 --> 00:10:48,168
You're not actually caring for each other.

103
00:10:48,649 --> 00:10:52,253
You're just trying to find your way, make money.

104
00:10:54,442 --> 00:11:08,745
So that means that any government or charitable effort that tries to do something about your basic physical or material well-being, people in need, would undermine the entrepreneurial spirit of competition.

105
00:11:09,446 --> 00:11:12,991
See, people have got to get out there and get into it.

106
00:11:14,760 --> 00:11:19,226
And of course, neoliberalism hates governments interfering with the markets.

107
00:11:19,647 --> 00:11:23,673
So there was this whole business about very few regulations.

108
00:11:23,793 --> 00:11:24,854
Well, we knew what happened.

109
00:11:25,394 --> 00:11:26,655
The banks went berserk.

110
00:11:27,017 --> 00:11:29,460
And then who had to step in to save them?

111
00:11:30,061 --> 00:11:32,543
Us, the poor ordinary punter.

112
00:11:34,706 --> 00:11:41,475
So you can see that this is diametrically opposed to anything that the Buddha would teach.

113
00:11:42,496 --> 00:11:43,418
And

114
00:11:43,937 --> 00:11:52,610
The wonderful thing is that, of course, people are highly stressed in that sort of system, all the way down from CSOs, all the way down to the ordinary worker.

115
00:11:53,230 --> 00:12:12,155
Now, it seems that the World Economic Forum at Davos, where the rich and the powerful, the high and mighty meet to decide how to rule the world, they were overjoyed to hear about mindfulness.

116
00:12:14,025 --> 00:12:18,152
So, you know, mindfulness would help people with their stress.

117
00:12:18,493 --> 00:12:19,374
So they began.

118
00:12:19,693 --> 00:12:27,947
So you began to tell all the workers who were stressed out, you've got to take a course in mindfulness and stress reduction.

119
00:12:28,788 --> 00:12:40,184
And if you happen to be even more stressed by even more stress, well, all you had to do was find a place in the office or somewhere and just sit there for a while and watch your breath and it would all disappear.

120
00:12:40,317 --> 00:12:46,253
as though stress were entirely a person's internal response to a situation.

121
00:12:46,693 --> 00:12:53,753
But as we know, the stress that's put upon you from the outside has a great deal to do with our own mental states.

122
00:12:55,522 --> 00:13:14,669
So this wonderful gift that the Buddha gave us of investigating our lives and our being in order to achieve complete liberation from suffering is now being used to support a system which is doing exactly the opposite.

123
00:13:16,493 --> 00:13:17,715
What an irony.

124
00:13:18,403 --> 00:13:28,383
And of course, what the neoliberal system is doing is the work of Mara.

125
00:13:28,403 --> 00:13:30,166
Now, Mara is the evil one.

126
00:13:30,706 --> 00:13:35,956
If you remember, just before the Buddha's liberation, Mara came and said,

127
00:13:35,937 --> 00:13:37,919
Come on, and gave him this great doubt.

128
00:13:37,940 --> 00:13:39,022
He said, come on, what are you doing?

129
00:13:39,121 --> 00:13:40,283
Why are you doing this?

130
00:13:40,303 --> 00:13:42,206
Why are you going through all this pain, this suffering?

131
00:13:42,527 --> 00:13:51,081
Why don't you get back to your family and get back to sensual pleasures and how it was in the old days before you took up this silly idea?

132
00:13:51,120 --> 00:13:54,245
And of course, the Buddha touches the earth.

133
00:13:54,767 --> 00:13:55,807
Now, this is the important thing.

134
00:13:55,847 --> 00:14:01,336
He touches the earth and the goddess of the earth arises.

135
00:14:01,317 --> 00:14:09,648
And says to Mara, no, the Buddha has every right to do this because he has perfected the virtue of generosity.

136
00:14:10,327 --> 00:14:24,866
OK, so in other words, the Buddha's, shall we say, commitment came from his desire also to free everybody from suffering.

137
00:14:25,947 --> 00:14:27,509
And this is really interesting.

138
00:14:27,894 --> 00:14:33,703
something that undermines the neoliberal agenda.

139
00:14:34,446 --> 00:14:39,653
The idea that we can actually be like citizens who are helping each other.

140
00:14:40,054 --> 00:14:47,746
So if you remember during the lockdown here, suddenly neighbors realized they could help themselves.

141
00:14:47,767 --> 00:14:48,508
It was unknown.

142
00:14:48,969 --> 00:14:52,053
You could actually knock on a neighbor's door and say, how are you doing?

143
00:14:52,114 --> 00:14:54,577
And be there to help them out.

144
00:14:55,975 --> 00:14:57,778
This was a new discovery, it seems.

145
00:15:01,842 --> 00:15:08,613
So now, just before I carry on with generosity, the question is, what can we personally do?

146
00:15:09,073 --> 00:15:12,378
Well, the obvious thing, of course, is to be aware of what we're buying.

147
00:15:12,798 --> 00:15:22,152
So, you know, not to support these satanic factories in Bangladesh and Cambodia and even in China.

148
00:15:22,890 --> 00:15:39,899
But coming back now to generosity, I'm sure you've noticed that when you do something out of a sense of care for yourself, like you might buy a warm jumper or something like that, there's always a feeling good about that.

149
00:15:39,958 --> 00:15:41,360
You feel good about yourself.

150
00:15:41,421 --> 00:15:43,144
You're caring for yourself.

151
00:15:43,342 --> 00:15:57,014
Have you noticed that when you care for somebody else, when you look after somebody else, when you buy something for somebody, when you give something for somebody or spend time for somebody else, the joy that comes from it is much more long lasting.

152
00:15:57,687 --> 00:16:10,962
And it's that shift towards going away from this me towards we is where we can begin to find a different sort of economic system.

153
00:16:11,423 --> 00:16:14,408
Of course, that sounds a bit glib, you know, me to we and all that.

154
00:16:16,250 --> 00:16:21,677
But basically, it's that sense of, you know, to bring back that sense of community.

155
00:16:22,898 --> 00:16:26,783
And I would just like to end this lovely quote that I've got from

156
00:16:28,078 --> 00:16:43,022
From the Buddha, if beings knew, as I knew, the results of giving and sharing, they would not eat without having given, nor would the stain of miserliness overcome their minds.

157
00:16:44,143 --> 00:16:54,558
Even if it were their last bite, their last mouthful, they would not eat without having shared, if there were someone to receive the gift.

158
00:16:54,792 --> 00:17:06,330
But because beings do not know this, as I know, the results of giving and sharing, they eat without having given and the stain of miserliness overcomes their mind.

159
00:17:10,417 --> 00:17:21,676
So it's possible, right, that we can have a life of joyfulness, which is a shared joy with people around us.

160
00:17:22,045 --> 00:17:31,013
And to get away from this very tight sense of this little self, like a little castle, which has to defend itself against everybody.

161
00:17:32,615 --> 00:17:46,208
And you see it in the new woke, you know, especially XR rebellion, which is trying to wake people up to recognizing that things, you know, things are getting worse.

162
00:17:46,268 --> 00:17:48,390
We have to do something about it.

163
00:17:48,791 --> 00:17:56,203
And you'll find great resistance from that, from those people who, of course, are committed to neoliberalism.

164
00:17:56,223 --> 00:18:01,612
So all we can hope for is a change of attitude.

165
00:18:02,733 --> 00:18:08,844
You'll get politicians saying, oh, well, what we need is better jobs and better housing.

166
00:18:09,023 --> 00:18:12,690
But that's all within the system of neoliberalism.

167
00:18:13,008 --> 00:18:24,805
So in a sense, if we're going to move towards something which is much more just, much more equitable, much more kind, much more caring, it's that fundamental attitude that has to change.

168
00:18:25,506 --> 00:18:37,142
And let's hope that when it does happen, because the seeds of destruction are within capitalism itself, when it does happen, hopefully...

169
00:18:37,122 --> 00:18:45,921
in the near future, let's just hope it's not another ideology, because that again will create problems.

170
00:18:46,823 --> 00:18:53,156
And what the Buddha is saying is, if you ground yourself in the right attitude,

171
00:18:53,136 --> 00:19:15,701
and you recognize that times, that situation and times are in a constant flux, then you can always come at a particular situation, not from some preset view and opinion, but from this attitude of compassion, of sympathetic joy, of caring, of love, for heaven's sake.

172
00:19:18,095 --> 00:19:35,090
Anyway, I hope my words have been of some assistance, that they have not caused even greater confusion, and that by your commitment to the good life of compassion and joy, you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

